<div class="article-section" id="6">
	<h1>Payments</h1>

	<h2>- What is a Direct debit?</h2>

	<p>Direct debits are a preferred way for merchants to request for consistent long or short term payments. This is done by a customer's permission for merchants to claim payments from the account. This can be canceled at any time through the app. We do suggest contacting the merchant to cancel the direct debit on their side so that they do not request the payment again</p>

	<h2>- How do I make a payment?</h2>

	<p>The payments will be made through your account, you can send the funds at any time you wish without contacting us directly. However there will be cut of times for particular payments such SEPA which is 2pm and will be sent the following day.</p>

	<h2>- What is a Faster payment?</h2>

	<p>Faster payments are made by yourself through the app. Once you have entered and confirmed the details, the payment will be sent immediately. The money will be received within minutes. Some banks can take 2 hours to clear the faster payment so please give the payment some time also double check all the details before sending the payment.</p>
</div>
<div class="article-section" id="7">
	<h1>Transfer</h1>

	<h2>- How do I correct a mistake or cancel a transfer?</h2>

	<p>Transfers can be canceled or corrected before the payment has been released. This can be done through the contact centre. However once the payment has been released we can try and make a payment recall but there is no guarantee the money will be returned.</p>

	<h2>- How can I check a transfer status?</h2>

	<p>There will be a live update on each transfer stating Pending/Successful.</p>
</div>
<div class="article-section" id="8">
	<h1>CHAPS & BACS</h1>

	<h2>- What is CHAPS?</h2>

	<p>Clearing House Automated Payment System is also known as CHAPS. These payments are usually for high-value transactions like buying a car or a property. The request for a CHAPS payment to be received the same day will be before 3pm. After 3pm will mean the payment will be received the following day.</p>

	<h2>- What is BACS?</h2>

	<p>BACS also known as Bankers’ Automated Clearing System. This service is mostly used to pay salaries, wages or benefits. This tends to be a preferred payment system for employee expenses, pension and tax credits. If a BACS transfer is expected then please allow 3 days for the payment to be received into your account.</p>
